{
  "answer": "**There is no passage in *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana* where Vairocana directly describes the hells.** \n\nVairocana (synonymous here with the sermon-giving Buddha, the Lord Jina/Sugata/Gautama at the Monastery of Enlightenment) instead commands the protagonist Kuñjarakarṇa to travel to Yama's realm and witness the hells firsthand, then report back for further instruction on *dharma*.[^1] Kuñjarakarṇa does so (Cantos 7–13), where the hells—including the City of Iron Earth, sword-trees, iron mountains, cauldrons, and torments like impaling, crushing, scorching, and *kiṅkara* attacks—are vividly narrated by the poet (not Vairocana).[^2] Yama later explains the causes of sin (body, speech, mind) and specific punishments (e.g., for the *gandharva* king Pūrṇavijaya).[^3]\n\nVairocana's own teachings focus on karma, the five souls (*ātmā* etc.), debts to gods/parents/teachers/world, unity of Buddhist/Śaiva/Ṛṣi deities (identifying himself as all-pervading), and paths to *mokṣa* via merit, vows, and non-dual wisdom—after Kuñjarakarṇa's return.[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paras. p-f907b3–p-423a28](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-f907b3).\n[^2]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paras. p-4f1644–p-61142e](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-4f1644) (City of Iron Earth, sword-grass, impaling, etc.).\n[^3]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paras. p-571653–p-50854d](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-571653) (Yama's explanations); [paras. p-c32761–p-890b15](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-c32761) (cauldron for Pūrṇavijaya).\n[^4]: *Kuñjarakarṇa Dharmakathana*, Chapter 1, [paras. p-6c6127–p-310540](/works/unknown-kunjarakarna-dharmakathana-894f4a/01/translation/#p-6c6127) (Vairocana's self-identification and teachings).",
